His
back
felt
stiff
from
lying
on
the
hard
catwalk.
Where's
Katherine?
Langdon
checked
his
Mickey
Mouse
watch.
It's
almost
time.
He
pulled
himself
to
his
feet,
peering
cautiously
over
the
banister
into
the
gaping
space
below.
"Katherine?"
he
called
out.
The
word
echoed
back
in
the
silence
of
the
deserted
Rotunda.
Retrieving
his
tweed
jacket
from
the
floor,
he
brushed
it
off
and
put
it
back
on.
He
checked
his
pockets.
The
iron
key
the
Architect
had
given
him
was
gone.
Making
his
way
back
around
the
walkway,
Langdon
headed
for
the
opening
the
Architect
had
shown
them
.
.
.
steep
metal
stairs
ascending
into
cramped
darkness.
He
began
to
climb.
Higher
and
higher
he
ascended.
Gradually
the
stairway
became
more
narrow
and
more
inclined.
Still
Langdon
pushed
on.
Just
a
little
farther.
The
steps
had
become
almost
ladderlike
now,
the
passage
frighteningly
constricted.
Finally,
the
stairs
ended,
and
Langdon
stepped
up
onto
a
small
